    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-26T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-26T17:00:00-05:00" n="401"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d401">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">824.01/445: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Boal</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">La Paz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-26T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 26, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 26—4:46 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>333. Andrade<note n="45" xml:id="d401fn45">Victor Andrade, Minister of
                        Labor.</note> told a member of the Legal Attaché’s office the following: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>The Junta is prepared to do anything to stay in power, believing that
                            when the truth is known recognition will follow.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Nonrecognition may be a good thing for Bolivia in the long run if it
                            forces Bolivians to rely on themselves and develop other resources than
                            tin. The suffering will be good for the character of Bolivian
                            people.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Bolivia’s rubber, tin and quinine will be sold to the United States as
                            before if the United States still wishes to buy.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Junta will attempt to remain friendly with United Nations rather than
                            turn abruptly toward Argentina. With patience Junta will await
                            recognition.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Some Junta members are still attempting to remove Céspedes<note n="46"
                                xml:id="d401fn46">Augusto de Céspedes, Secretary General of the
                                Junta.</note> and Montenegro<note n="47" xml:id="d401fn47">Carlos
                                Montenegro, Minister of Agriculture.</note> but early action appears
                            unlikely.</item>
                        <pb facs="0457" n="443" xml:id="pg_443"/>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>Junta will not call elections until election laws are changed to
                            increase electorate from 1,000 to approximately 400,000 of total
                            population.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Boal</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
